title: California's sweeping new social policies could set trend
text: > Health California's sweeping new social policies could set trend FILE - In this Sept. 9, 2015, file photo, Debbie Ziegler holds a photo of her daughter, Brittany Maynard, as she receives congratulations from Ellen Pontac, left, after a right-to die measure they supported was approved by the state Assembly in Sacramento, Calif. California enacted some of the nation's most aggressive social polices this year, including the bill that allows terminally ill people the right to take life-ending medications. Maynard moved to Oregon from California to legally end her life in 2014. (AP Photo/Rich Pedroncelli, File)
